A '''figure of thought''' ({{lang-la|figurae sententiarum}}, {{lang-el|schemata dianoias}}) is a [[rhetorical device]] sometimes distinguished from [[figure of speech]].<ref>Gideon O. Burton, [http://rhetoric.byu.edu/Figures/Figures%20of%20Speech-Thought.htm "Figures of speech/figures of thought"], ''Silva Rhetoricae'', Brigham Young University</ref> In another sense the term has been used in the study of diagrams and drawings.<ref>Gerhard Dirmoser, [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-7091-0803-1_12#page-1 "Figures of Thought: The Use of Diagrams in Science and Art"], in "Drawing a Hypothesis", pp. 153-160</ref>

==Application to Latin literature==
It may be difficult to draw the distinction between figures of speech and figures of thought, especially when the primary area of inquiry is [[poetry]] rather than a prose composition, which adheres to the rules of rhetorical theory that were for the most part created in their fullest articulation in the age of [[Quintilian]] (c. 35 – c. 100). In their approach to language, the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] poets ([[Horace]], [[Catullus]], [[Propertius]], [[Tibullus]]) did not distinguish between ''[[inventio]]'' and ''[[elocutio]]'', which explains somewhat our confusion between figures of thought and figures of speech. The latter are exemplified most immediately by conceptual substitutions, such as [[metaphor]] or [[synecdoche]], but if we consider not just the mere ''linguistic'' aspect of the substitution and focus most closely on the concepts themselves, then we may perceive the comprehensiveness of the conceptual for the poet, who operates with words to extend and amplify the potential semantics of poetic output.

==Uses of the term==
[[Ananda Coomaraswamy]] used the term in relation to the philosophy of [[Plato]]:

<blockquote>
"Plato’s dialectic makes continual use of figures of speech, which are really figures of thought."<ref>[http://www.studiesincomparativereligion.com/Public/articles/A_Figure_of_Speech_or_a_Figure_of_Thought_Part_1-by_Ananda_Coomaraswamy.aspx "A Figure of Speech, or a Figure of Thought?"], Studies in Comparative Religion, Vol. 6, No. 1, Winter 1972</ref>
</blockquote>

The scholar of [[Latin literature]] Gordon Williams (died 2010)<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2744529.ece "Gordon Williams: Scholar who introduced many to the pleasures of Latin poetry" (obituary)], The Times (London), 29 September 2010</ref> published a study titled ''Figures of Thought in Roman Poetry'' (1980), stating in the introduction:

<blockquote>
"[[Language]] was subject to ordering by exhaustive description of vocabulary, syntax, and figures. The content was likewise subject to ordering by the rules of ''[[inventio]]'' (the technique by which all the latent or inherent possibilities in a given idea or cluster of ideas could be 'discovered' and exploited)."<ref>
{{cite book | last = Williams | first = Gordon | year = 1980 | title = Figures of Thought in Roman Poetry 
| publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven and London | isbn = 0-300-02456-8
}}
</ref>
</blockquote>

A collection of drawings by Nikolaus Gansterer (2011) was titled "Drawing a Hypothesis: Figures of Thought".<ref>[https://www.a-n.co.uk/reviews/drawing-a-hypothesis-figures-of-thought "Drawing a Hypothesis: Figures of thought"], a-n The Artists Information Company, 19 April 2012</ref>

